Pleopods (Fig. 5F, G, H, I). Gonopod 1 widest at base; both subterminal and terminal segments tapering, ending with sharp point. Medial margin fairly straight displaying extrusion near base; lateral margin concave relative to midline; both margins hirsute. Groove extending almost entire length of gonopod, visible on dorsal surface, lined with setae. Gonopod 1 terminal segment long (0.31 times length of subterminal segment), curving outwards (i.e. away from midline) when viewed dorsally. Gonopod 2 consisting of two segments. Distal segment very long (0.57 times length of basal seg 
ment
), slim; basal segment with wide elongated base sharply becoming narrow around 0.4 of length; narrow process forming at this point leading to distal segment.
